 the world adore The Boss. Mary Climbs In illuminates this once overlooked but increasingly important and multi-faceted conversation about female audiences for Springsteen’s music. Drawing on unique surveys of fans themselves, the study offers insight into women’s experiences in their own voices. Authors Lorraine Mangione and Donna Luff explore the depth of women fans’ connection to Springsteen and the profound ways this connection has shaped their lives. Reflections from fans enliven each page as readers journey through the camaraderie and joy of concerts, the sorrow and confusion of personal loss and suffering, the love and closeness of community, and the search for meaning and for the self. Viewed through a psychological lens, women fans’ relationship with Springsteen is revealed in all its complexity as never before. Mary Climbs In is an important interdisciplinary contribution to the growing field of Springsteen studies and a must-read for any fan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRock musicxPsychological aspects. 0aWomen rock music fansxPsychology. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  agender, female fans, fandom, media studies, music.  awomen, fans, fan culture, Bruce Springsteen, sociology, psychology.1 aLuff, Donna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079130340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197882721940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978827219423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978827219/original  a978-3-11-079130-3  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles